Mixed-effects models can have a lot of pros and few cons, is what Im telling you.

What is a Mixed-Effects Model?

A mixed-effects model is mixed because it contains two kinds of effects:

  • Fixed Effects: These are the predictors in a regression; the variables we want to test.
  • Random Effects: These are grouping factors, variables that represent groups or categories that exist in the data (specifically the dependent variable). Random effects help us to account for non-independence in our data.

Nested data

Weve talked about within-subjects data already: data where multiple data points come from the same source (e.g.the same subject). Within-subjects data is nested data, as if the data points are fragile little eggs gently nested within the person who provided those data points.

If data is nested, then it is not independent. What makes data non-independent? Well, lets start by considering some examples of data that is independent:

  • A large-scale survey randomly samples from the entire US population. Each person is asked which of two candidates they plan to vote for. (Its a two party system. You have to vote for one of us!)
  • A doctor randomly measures the blood pressure of 100 people to see whether males or females are at greater risk of hypertension.

In independent data, each observation is separate from each other observation - there is no reason to think that one data point could be logically grouped with another. This means that each participant gives only one data point.

Most data is not independent. Instead, the data can be grouped in some way.

  • A longitudinal study of child nutrition collects data on the diets of 100 children once a year for 10 years. So, each child gives 10 data points to the study. These data points are not independent, because they come from the same child.
  • A farmer is taking a sample of his potato crop to see how well it is doing. He takes 10 potatoes from each of his 5 fields. Because each group of 10 potatoes comes from the same field, these potatoes are not independent observations.
  • A state official is analyzing the results of a state-wide high school science test. Although each student only provides one data point, the students can be logically grouped depending on which high school they attend. Since different high schools differ in the quality of their science instruction (as well as in many other ways), the scores of the students who attend a given high school are not truly independent of each other.
  • A group of 20 language-impaired children take a picture naming test, and the therapist examines their accuracy at naming each of the 100 pictures. Because the same pictures were used for each participant, there are 20 observations for each picture. These data points are not independent, because they are all in reponse to the same picture.

Data like this that contains groups of inter-related data points is known as nested data. Mixed-effects models are tailor-made to handle nested data.


Sometimes data can be nested within nests:

  • An educational psychologist is comparing two instructional techniques. Students in 6 different classrooms are taught a history lesson using method A for one unit and method B for the other unit. After each unit, the students take a test. So, each student provides two data points, one after each unit. These two data points are nested within student. But the students themselves are nested within classrooms - students in the same classroom have the same teacher, so their scores are not independent of each other. Thats two nests: student and classroom.

Other times a given data point can fit into several different nests.

  • A cognitive psychologist has 50 participants read 20 different passages and assesses their comprehension; Each participant answers 5 comprehension questions about each passage. So, the answers to the questions are nested within participant. But they are also nested (separately) within text passage, because responses to the same texts are not independent of each other.

Nested data is actually quite common. In fact, while many textbook examples are independent data, I would argue that most real-world data sets are nested data.

Random Effects vs.Fixed Effects

Now that we know what nested data is, we are ready to discuss random effects. A random effect is a parameter in our model that accounts for the nested character of our data. In other words, a random effect tells the model which data points are nested and not independent.

How are fixed effects and random effects different?

In short, fixed effects represent the variables we are interested in, while random effects represent the variables we think might affect the outcome of our study but that we dont care about directly.

Fixed Effects Random Effects
Is related to our hypothesis Is NOT related to our hypothesis
Represents a variable we want to test Is a nuisance variable that we want to control for
Values were specifically chosen Values were selected at random from a larger group
Can be either categorical or continuous MUST be categorical

Imagine a simple study where we measure how many hours each student studies for each of the 10 quizzes they take in our class, and we want to see if this predicts quiz scores. Study Time is obviously a fixed effect; we care about it, and we want to test it.

But do we care about Student? Obviously we care about students as human beings, at least to the extent necessary to avoid being called a sociopath. But we are not interested in the students as a fixed effect; we didnt mention the students in our hypothesis, and we wont write a paper entitled How Tim Did on His Quizzes. The students represent the sample, and we want to generalize beyond these individual students to the population as a whole. Thats why student is a good random effect in this study.

We do know that the students differ from each other in many ways: age, IQ, sleep habits, educational background, stress, mental health, number of parasocial relationships with musician-celebrities, and more. Our study isnt about these things, but we know they can affect quiz scores. We could try to measure them all and put them into a regression as co-variates, but we dont have to! Instead, we can just make student a random effect. As youll see, adding random effects makes adjustments to our model based on who is taking the quizzes. This effectively controls for all the ways that each student differs from each other student, and allows us to focus on whats important: the fixed effects.

Lets practice figuring out whether some variable is a fixed or random effect.

Example 1: Reaction Time Data

Heres another example from the heplots package: a dataset called ReactTime. In this dataset, participants responded to stimuli presented at different angles. Sometimes noise was present, sometimes not.

We have 4 columns in this dataset: Subject, Angle, Noise, and Reaction_Time. Reaction_Time is the dependent variable.

Subject is our random effect - since each subject provided multiple data points, we want to group the data by Subject. Subject is NOT a fixed effect because its not the thing were studying; were not trying to learn something about how Subject influences Reaction_Time.

Like Subject, Angle and Noise are repeated in the data, but they are not random effects - Angle and Noise are fixed effects. Why? Because we chose these values specifically - we want to learn how Angle and Noise influence Reaction_Time.

Also, the Subjects is this study were randomly chosen from a larger population of people, so they should be a random effect. The values of Angle and Noise were specifically chosen by the person who set up the study - they were fixed by the experimenter. If you were to redo this study, you would have different subjects, but the same values for Angle and Noise.

Example 2: Sleep Study

Consider our hypothetical sleep study, above. In this example, we decided that Subject and Night were random effects. Subject is a random effect in this study for the same reason it was a random effect in the Reaction Time study. Night is a random effect because 1) it is a grouping factor - it is repeated multiple times in the data and 2) we dont want to test it directly. The study is not about whether people had caffeine on night 1 or night 2. In fact, Night was randomized because we dont want it to have an effect on our results. Since it was randomized, it should be a random effect.

But Caffeine is a fixed effect because 1) its the variable we care about and want to test and 2) we, as the experimenters, fixed (decided on) the different values for Caffeine.

Example 3: Empathy

In our hypothetical empathy study above, participants read one of 4 different Books from 2 different Genres: Literary Fiction and Non-Fiction. Book is a random effect because 1) we dont care about those books specifically and 2) we could have chosen different books - these books were selected at random from the broader Genre. Genre is a fixed effect because 1) this is the variable we care about and want to test and 2) we specifically chose these two Genres to include in our study.

Other (inferior) ways to handle nested data

So mixed-effects models are the best way to handle nested data. But there are others. Weve already seen a couple of other ways to handle nested data:

  • Paired-sample t-tests are used when both observations come from the same subject (i.e.the observations are nested within subject).
  • Repeated-measures ANOVAs include an additional error term that acknowledges the nested nature of the data set.

However, these methods are highly restricted in the kinds of nested data they can handle. Paired-sample t-tests can only handle a single nesting factor, and only two observations per nest. Repeated-measures ANOVAs can accept more observations per nest, but again can only handle a single nest at a time. Mixed-effects models do not suffer from these limitations.

What do we need to know about mixed-effects models

We learned previously that there are 4 things we need to know about any statistical test:

  • What variables can the test handle?
  • What statistic does the test generate?
  • What distribution does the test use?
  • What arguments does the R function require?

Lets talk about these 4 needs in relation to our next test: mixed effects models.

One thing you will notice quickly is that mixed-effects models are highly similar to regression. In fact, everything you just learned about regression applies directly to mixed-effects models. Theyre really just a fancy regression specifically made for nested data.

Variables

Dependent Variables

You should know what to expect here at this point: a mixed-effects model usually takes a single numeric dependent variable.

Independent/Predictor Variables (Fixed Effects)

Mixed-effects models are just like regression: they can take any number of both categorical and continuous variables as fixed effects.

Statistic

Again, just like regression: the t statistic is used here.

BUT obtaining the t statistic for mixed-effects models is a bit more complicated.

  1. Find the parameters:
    • The estimate (i.e.regression coefficient, slope of the line)
    • The standard error
  2. Divide the estimate by the standard error to get the t value
  3. Figure out the degrees of freedom

1. Find the Parameters

The regression coefficient and standard error are obtained differently in mixed-effects models than in regression. Regression uses the ordinary least squares (OLS) method for obtaining the regression coefficient and standard error. This method is based on minimizing the sum of squared residuals, as we saw earlier. This method uses explicit equations, and so it is possible (although not fun) to compute regression coefficients by hand.

Mixed-effects models use a different method called restricted maximum likelihood (REML) instead. Here are a few highlights of this method:

  • Ill use the word parameter a lot in this section. A model parameter is some number the model generates from the data, such as an intercept, a coefficient, or a standard error. These are numbers that can vary, and if you change them you have a different model.
  • You need a computer to do REML for you - theres no simple formula you can use.
  • The computer works iteratively, going through repeated stages to try and fit the model.
  • In the first iteration, the computer makes an educated guess on what a parameter should be, then tests that guess against the data to see if it is a good guess
  • On subsequent iterations, the computer adjusts the parameter based on the results of previous iterations, moving it back and forth repeatedly until it converges on the number that best fits the data.

Consider the graph below, which shows how the parameter estimates changed across the iterations. Notice how the estimate of the fixed effect (top panel, red circles) starts out higher, fluctuates for a while, and then eventually settles into a pretty stable pattern. This settling into a stable pattern is called convergence - the model has found the best number for this parameter.

You can see this same general trend - starting out with a guess and then adjusting it over time until the guess remains the same for several iterations - in the bottom 2 panels (standard errors).

The intercept (2nd panel, blue circles) converged immediately - the models guess was right the first time.

How convergence works

Mixed Models and the Problem of Convergence


Because the parameters are discovered via an iterative process rather than computed, it is sometimes possible that the model never converges on a best solution. In other words, sometimes the computer cant decide which number best fits the data. When this happens, we say that the model did not converge or failed to converge.

Heres what non-convergence looks like:

Notice how the parameters - especially the fixed effect - never really settle on a good number. When this happens, the model output will give you a warning, which will look something like this:

## Warning in checkConv(attr(opt, "derivs"), opt$par, ctrl = control$checkConv, : Model failed to
## converge with max|grad| = 1.88306 (tol = 0.002, component 1)
## Warning in checkConv(attr(opt, "derivs"), opt$par, ctrl = control$checkConv, : Model is nearly unidentifiable: very large eigenvalue
##  - Rescale variables?

This error means that the model couldnt settle on one or more parameters.

Other times, you might experience a related error; a warning about singular fits. This one isnt as bad - it just means you dont need some of your random effects parameters, because they are not doing much for the model.

## boundary (singular) fit: see help('isSingular')

What should you do about these errors?

In both cases, the most likely problem is that your model is overfitted: there are too many parameters for the data. In other words, you need to simplify the model. Usually, this means simplifying the random effects. Take out random slopes first, then move on to random intercepts. What are random slopes and intercepts? Well get to that in a moment.

Nerdy Aside: Some people argue that the random effects should be left in even if the model doesnt converge, and that other changes should be made, such as using a different optimizer to help the model converge. For now, lets just stick with taking out random effects until the model converges - but if you find yourself regularly using mixed-effects models youll want to find out more about best practices here.

The other problem: speed

Because mixed-effects models use an iterative process to converge on the model parameters, it means that these models need much more computing power than other statistical methods. In other words, be prepared to wait a while if you are running a mixed-effects model. Ideally, you want to run these on the best computer you have access to.

2. Divide the estimate by the standard error to get the t value

Once your model has converged and provided you with estimates and standard errors, getting the t-values is easy.

This step is the same as in regression.

3. Figure out the degrees of freedom

This step is NOT the same as in regression. Figuring out the degrees of freedom in a mixed-effects model is not a trivial task. Is it the number of data points? No, because the data points are not independent - some degrees of freedom have been lost. How many? Perhaps the degrees of freedom should be based on the number of groups instead, or on some combination of those two numbers. Also, many data sets are not balanced, so there are different numbers of observations in each group. This further complicates the calculation of the degrees of freedom.

So by default R just doesnt calculate degrees of freedom. It just gives you a t value and leaves you to fend for yourself.

One way you can deal with that is to use an approximation method to estimate the degrees of freedom. By loading the lmerTest package, we can tell R to give us a good guess about what the degrees of freedom should be for each fixed effect. If you want more information, heres a paper for you: (https://link.springer.com/article/10.3758/s13428-016-0809-y)

  1. Why doesnt R want to give us the degrees of freedom for mixed-effects models? What do we have to do to convince R to approximate the degrees of freedom?

Distribution

Like regression, mixed models use the t distribution.

Once we have our t-statistic and degrees of freedom, we can use the t distribution to obtain some p-values.

Arguments

  1. Load packages
  2. Set up a Regression

  4. Add Random Slopes

1. Load Packages

To start, we need to load some packages. Well load two:

  • lme4, the package that lets us do mixed modeling
  • lmerTest, the package that helps us get p values for our models
if (!require("lme4")) install.packages("lme4")
library(lme4) # This one lets you do mixed-effects models
if (!require("lmerTest")) install.packages("lmerTest")
library(lmerTest) # This one gives you p-values

3. Add Random Intercepts

Now lets fit a mixed-effects model to the same data. Well do two things.

  1. Change lm to lmer to tell R that this is a mixed model, not a normal regression.

Ive heard lmer pronounced as elmer or as lemur. Your choice, I guess. Are you a looney tunes Elmer Fudd fan or do you like king Julien from Madagascar?

  1. We will add random intercepts for Subject.

In papers, you will see this referred to as random by-Subject intercepts.

sleep.lmer <- lmer(Reaction ~ Days + (1 | Subject), data = sleepstudy)

Notice the format for including a random effect. The grouping variable (Subject) is encased in parentheses with a vertical bar - | - in front of it.

The 1 in front of the | represents the intercept. So the (1 | Subject) part of our formula means: use Subject as a random effect, and include by-subject intercepts (i.e.separate intercepts for each subject).

How do the results of our mixed-effects model differ from the simple regression above?

Our regression model (above) fitted a single line to all the data points. But our mixed effect model is smarter; it knowns (because we told it) that the data points are nested within Subjects. This is represented in the graph below by the different colored points.

We also told the model to give each Subject their own intercept. Remember that a line has two properties:

  • The slope, which represents the change in Y divided by the change in X (the rise over the run).
  • The intercept, which represents the value of Y when X = 0.

In our model, we have fitted a separate regression line to each Subject. You can see these lines on the graph below. The lines all have the same slope (for now), but different intercepts; they cross the Y axis at different points.

## Warning: Using `size` aesthetic for lines was deprecated in ggplot2 3.4.0.
##  Please use `linewidth` instead.
## This warning is displayed once every 8 hours.
## Call `lifecycle::last_lifecycle_warnings()` to see where this warning was generated.


Take a moment and ask yourself: what does it mean that Subject 337 has a higher intercept than Subject 309?

What DOES it mean that Subject 337 has a higher intercept than Subject 309?

The intercept represents the value of Y (Reaction) when X (Days without sleep) equals 0. In other words, the intercept tells us what the subjects reaction time was at day 0 - before they were deprived of sleep. People differ in their reaction time - some people are faster than other people. Adding random intercepts allows our model to account for this.

Comparing mixed models to simple regression

What happens when we add these random intercepts? When we have one line for each group instead of just one line for all of the data, we can more closely match the lines to the data. In other words, we have less variance unexplained. Here are three ways to show you that this is true:

  1. Residuals
  2. AIC
  3. R2

Residuals

You remember what residuals are: the difference in Y between the points and the lines. Lets compare the regression residuals to the mixed model residuals:

## [1] "Regression Residuals"
##     Min.  1st Qu.   Median     Mean  3rd Qu.     Max. 
## -110.848  -27.483    1.546    0.000   26.142  139.953
## [1] "Mixed Model Residuals"
##     Min.  1st Qu.   Median     Mean  3rd Qu.     Max. 
## -3.22567 -0.55288  0.01085  0.00000  0.51880  4.25062

The Min and Max residuals are MUCH larger for regression than for the mixed model.

AIC

We talked previously about AIC, the Akaike Information Criterion. As you undoubtedly recall, the AIC is a measure of how much variance is left unaccounted for by the model. So, lower AIC is better. Lets compare our models again:

Regression Mixed Model
1906.2930564 1794.4650854

The AIC is smaller for the mixed model.

R2

And finally, R2 is a measure that tells us how much variance we have accounted for with the model. In this sense, it is the opposite of the AIC: larger R2 means a better model.

To get the R2 for our mixed model, we need to load the MuMIn package. Add this code to your startup chunk:

if(!require("MuMIn")) install.packages("MuMIn")
library(MuMIn)

And now to compare our models:

r.squaredGLMM(sleep.regression)
##            R2m       R2c
## [1,] 0.2853276 0.2853276
r.squaredGLMM(sleep.lmer)
##            R2m       R2c
## [1,] 0.2798856 0.7042555

Notice that the rsquared.GLMM() function gives us 2 R2 values: R2m and R2c. R2m is the R2 value for the fixed effects only. R2c is the R2 value for the fixed and random effects together. Notice that these numbers are the same for the regression model, since there are no random effects in that model; all variance explained comes from the fixed effects.

Also notice that the R2c is a LOT bigger for the mixed model than for the regression; weve jumped from about 28% of the variance explained to more than 70% of the variance explained!

4. Add Random Slopes

Now lets add random slopes to our model.

Random slopes allow the slope to vary for each Subject.

sleep.lmer.slopes <- lmer(Reaction ~ Days + (1 + Days | Subject), data = sleepstudy)

Notice the syntax here. We started with random intercepts (1 | Subject). Then we added in the variable Days that we had already included as a fixed effect: (1 + Days | Subject).

Heres what this looks like graphically:


Notice how each Subjects line now has a different intercept AND a different slope.

As we have seen, a random intercept allows each Subject to have a different baseline level of the dependent variable (i.e.a different Reaction time).

Take a moment and ask yourself: what does it mean if Subject 337 has a steeper slope than Subject 309? What does that say about how 337 and 309 responded to sleep deprivation?

What DOES having a different slope for each Subject represent?

A random slope allows each Subject to have a different response to a fixed effect. In other words, maybe some subjects handled the sleep deprivation better than others. Some subjects reaction time might have increased quickly over the days, indicating that they got slower more rapidly, a strong response to sleep deprivation. Other subjects reaction time increased more slowly, indicating that they were less affected by the sleep deprivation.

Heres the AIC and R2 for comparing the random intercepts model to the random slopes model (which also has random intercepts). What do these numbers tell us?

So, lets look at the output of this model more closely.

There are several different sections to our data:

  • The first section describes the model, formula, and data
  • The second section gives the REML criterion - how well does the model fit the data. This number isnt really useful - it cannot be compared across models with different fixed effect structures. Other measures like AIC and R2 are better.
  • A summary of the residuals. This should be familiar from the regression output.
  • A summary of the random effects. We can see the standard deviation for the random intercept, the random slope for Days, and the correlation between the two. We also see the standard deviation of the residuals - variance left unexplained even after considering the random effects.
  • The Fixed Effects. This corresponds to the Coefficients portion of the regression output, and it the part we are most interested in.
  • Correlation of fixed effects. This tells us which fixed effects were correlated. It can be useful for diagnosing collinearity, but otherwise just skip it.

The Fixed Effects section looks almost the same as a regression, with one additional column - df (degrees of freedom). This column and the p-values column P(<|t|) will only appear if youve loaded the lmerTest package. These columns can be interpreted in the same way as a regression.

Model Levels

Even though the model was fitting multiple lines to the data, we only got one intercept and one slope for Days. Why?

Well, the model works in two stages, or levels (which is why its sometimes called a multilevel model).

  • Level 1: individual data points. A line is fitted to the data points within each group.
  • Level 2: groups. The intercepts and slopes for each group are averaged together to get an overall intercept and slope.

This distinction is a useful one, and can be applied to our fixed effects, too.

  • Days is a Level 1 variable because it applies to the individual data points; data within a group (Subject) can have different values for Days.
  • A variable such as Age would be a Level 2 variable because it applies to the groups, not to the individual data points. All data within a group would have the same value for Age, since Age applies to the grouping variable Subject.

Evaluating Your Model

Most of what you learned about evaluating regression models applies here as well. You still need to:

  1. Fit Your Model, removing parameters that dont contribute to the model
  2. Check for (and fix) collinearity
  3. Assess Model Fit

Thee steps are similar to what we did for regression, but we have to do them a bit differently.

Fit Your Model

We cant just use the step() function to fit lmers, UNLESS we have loaded the lmerTest package. This is where the lmerTest package comes in handy again. The step() function tests all your random effects to see if they should be retained in the model. It then tests all of your fixed effects. We nest the step() function inside the get_model() function in order to pull out and save the final version of the model that step() decides on.

Nerdy aside: What the step function is doing is using Likelihood Ratio Tests to compare a model with each random or fixed effect to a model without that random or fixed effect, to see if the overall model fit is better with that effect in. If the model isnt improved by this effect, it is removed. This is one way to fit mixed-effects models, but it isnt the only way! In fact, this is another area of debate on how to properly use mixed-effects models. For now, just report that you used the step() function from lmerTest to fit your model, and be prepared to adopt new best practices in the future - if everyone ever comes to an agreement on what those best practices are.

sleep.lmer.step <- get_model(step(sleep.lmer.slopes))
summary(sleep.lmer.step)
## Linear mixed model fit by REML. t-tests use Satterthwaite's method ['lmerModLmerTest']

Looks like we want the random slopes and intercept. And were keeping Days as a fixed effect, too. We saw above that all of these parameters improved the model fit, so we shouldnt be surprised at this outcome.

Check for collinearity

We can check for collinearity the same way we did for regression: with the vif function.

vif(sleep.lmer.step)

We get an error here because there is only 1 fixed effect. There cannot be any collinearity between variables when there is only one variable!

Describing Mixed Model Results

Now that you have finalized your mixed-effects model, its time to report the results. We need to report information for the model as a whole, as well as the individual predictors:

Model as a Whole:

  • What was the dependent variable?
  • What were the fixed effects
    • What transformations (such as centering) were applied?
    • What interactions were included?
  • What were the random effects?
  • How was model fitting accomplished?
    • What fixed effects and/or interactions were discarded during model fitting?
    • What random effects were discarded during model fitting
  • How well does the final model fit the data?
  • Report AIC and/or R2c.

For each predictor and interaction, we need to report the following:

  • The estimate
  • The standard error
  • The t value.
  • the p value.
  • A plain-language description of the interpretation.

Heres how we might describe our results:

A mixed-effects model was fitted to the data, with Reaction time as the dependent variable. The model included Days of sleep deprivation as a fixed effect. Random by-Subject intercepts were included in the model, as were random by-Subject slopes for Days. The fixed and random effects structure were fitted using the step() function from the lmerTest package. All fixed and random effects were retained. The R2 for the final model was 0.799.

And now to describe the individual results:

The effect of Days was significant (Estimate = 10.47, SE = 1.55, t = 6.77, p < .001), indicating that for each day of sleep deprivation, reaction time increased by about 10 milliseconds on average.

Some More Step-by-Step Examples

Vocab Growth

Lets start with the VocabGrowth data set. Well include the following variables

  • Dependent Variable: Vocab_Score, a number representing a childs vocabulary
  • Predictor 1: Grade, a number representing the childs current grade level
  • Random Effect 1: Student, a factor representing which participant the data came from

Well start with a maximal model that includes all possible random slopes as well as a random intercept and a fixed effect for Grade.

LongVocabGrowth <- VocabGrowth %>% mutate(Student = row.names(.)) %>% relocate(Student) %>% 
  pivot_longer(cols = 2:ncol(.), names_to = c("Grade"), values_to = "Vocab_Score") %>% mutate(Grade = gsub("grade", "", Grade), Grade = as.numeric(Grade))

vocab.lmer <- lmer(Vocab_Score ~ scale(Grade, scale = FALSE) + (1 + scale(Grade, scale = FALSE) |Student), data = LongVocabGrowth)

Reaction Time

Now lets look at the ReactTime data set. Well include the following variables

  • Dependent Variable: ReactTime, a number representing a participants speed to react the the stimulus
  • Fixed Effect 1: Angle, how much the stimulus was tilted
  • Fixed Effect 2: Noise, whether some visual noise was present to make it harder to see the stimulus
  • Fixed Effect 3: The interaction of Angle and Noise counts as a separate fixed effect.
  • Random Effect 1: Subject, a factor representing which participant the data came from

Well start with a maximal model that includes all possible random slopes for all 3 fixed effects (notice the * between Angle and Noise, this represents a random slope for the intercept) as well as random by-subject intercepts.

LongReactData <- ReactTime %>% mutate(Subject = row.names(.)) %>% relocate(Subject) %>% 
  pivot_longer(cols = 2:ncol(.), names_to = c("Angle", "Noise"), names_sep = "N", values_to = "Reaction_Time") %>%
  mutate(Noise = case_when(
    Noise == "A" ~ "Absent", 
    Noise == "P" ~ "Present",
    TRUE ~ NA
  ), Angle = gsub("deg", "", Angle), Angle = as.numeric(Angle))

react.lmer <- lmer(Reaction_Time ~ 1 + Angle * Noise + (1 + Angle * Noise |Subject), data = LongReactData)
## boundary (singular) fit: see help('isSingular')

Describing the Results

Heres how we might describe our sleep results:

A mixed-effects model was fitted to the data, with reaction time as the dependent variable. The model included Angle of presentation as a continuous fixed effect and Noise (Levels: Absent or Present) as a categorical fixed effect. Random by-Subject intercepts were also included in the model, as were random by-Subject slopes for Angle. The fixed and random effects structure were fitted using the step() function from the lmerTest package. The R2 for the final model was 0.88.

And now to describe the individual results:

The effect of Angle was significant (Estimate = 8.25, SE = 2.78, t = 2.92, p = .0051), indicating that as the Angle of presentation increased, reaction times increased, at a rate of about 8.25 milliseconds per degree. The effect of Noise was not significant (Estimate = 36, SE = 28.47, t = 1.26, p = .22), indicating that visual noise had no influence on reaction times when the Angle was 0. However, a significant interaction of Angle and Noise (Estimate = 25.5, SE = 3.93, t = 6.5, p < .001) indicated that the effect of Angle was stronger in the Noise Present condition, so that as Angle increased, reaction times in the two Noise conditions diverged (see Figure 1).

Describing the Results

Heres how we might describe our sleep results:

A mixed-effects model was fitted to the data, with langauge score as the dependent variable. The model included three continuous fixed effects - overall IQ, verbal IQ, student SES, and SchoolSES - as well as two categorical variables - sex and Minority Status (Yes/No). SchoolSES and Minority Status did not contribute to the model, and were removed. Random by-School intercepts were included in the model, but no random slopes were included as they prevented the model from converging. The fixed and random effects structure were fitted using the step() functions from the lmerTest package, respectively. The R2 for the final model was 0.54.

And now to describe the individual results:

The effect of overall IQ was significant (Estimate = 0.72, SE = 0.067, t = 10.88, p < .001), indicating that for each point increase in overall IQ, language score increased by 0.7. Verbal IQ also separately predicted language score (Estimate = 1.97, SE = 0.073, t = 26.87, p < .001), indicating that language scores went up almost 2 points for each point increase in verbal IQ. Sex was also predictive of language skill (Estimate = 2.97, SE = 0.26, t = 11.39, p < .001) indicating that whichever sex was originally coded as 1 scores about 3 points higher on the language test. Finally, SES was predictive of language score (Estimate = 0.14, SE = 0.014, t = 9.91, p < .001), indicating that for each unit increase in SES, langauge scores went up by 0.14 points.

Flights

Lets finish up with our familiar flights data from the nycflights13 package. Well include the following variables

  • Dependent Variable: Arrival delay (arr_delay), a number representing how late the flight was to arrive at its destination
  • Predictor 1: Departure delay (dep_delay), a number representing how late the flight was leaving
  • Predictor 2: Scheduled arrival time (sched_arr_time), a number representing when the flight was expected to arrive; larger numbers mean later flights.
  • Predictor 3: Origin, the airport the flight left from (Levels: EWA, LGA, JFK)
  • Predictor 4: Air time (air_time), a number representing how many minutes the flight was in the air.
  • Random Effect 1: Carrier, a factor representing which airline operated the flight
  • Random Effect 2: Destination (dest), a factor representing the airport the flight was going to.

Before we start, lets consider Origin. We are putting it in as a fixed effect. However, we could have easily made it a random effect, since the flights were definitely grouped by which airport they left from. Why make it a fixed effect instead of a random one? It depends entirely on our goals. If we care about origin and want to know which of the three NYC airports tends to have later-arriving flights, we need to test this by including origin as a fixed effect. On the other hand, if we dont really care about testing the origin variable but we want to control for it, then we should make it a random effect; this is exactly what we have done for carrier and destination.

Fitting the Model

Normally, we would start with a full or maximal model that includes all our fixed effects, two grouping factors (carrier, which means the airline, and dest, which means the flights destination), and all possible random slopes. However, in this case such a model would take forever to run! So this time we will start with no random slopes.

library(nycflights13)
flights.lmer <- lmer(arr_delay ~ dep_delay + sched_arr_time + origin + air_time + (1 | carrier) + (1 | dest), data = flights)

Even this one takes a while to run.

Fitting the Model

Now we can add the random slopes one at a time and test the model to see if that slope should remain in the model. Ive done this for you. It took a while.

Spoiler alert: we dont need any random slopes in this model.

Now lets see if we need any fixed effects:

Describing the Results

Heres how we might describe our results:

A mixed-effects model was fitted to the data, with arrival delay as the dependent variable. The model included three continuous fixed effects - departure delay, scheduled arrival time, and air time - as well as origin, a factor representing which airport the flight had departed from (EWR, LGA, or JFK). Random by-Carrier and by-Destination intercepts were included in the model, but no random slopes were included as they prevented the model from converging. The fixed and random effects structure were fitted using the step() function from the lmerTest package. All fixed effects and random intercepts were included in the final model. The R2 for the final model was 0.985.

And now to describe the individual results:

The effect of Departure Delay was significant (Estimate = 1.024, SE = 0.0007, t = 1546, p < .001), indicating that for each minute of departure delay, the arrival was delayed by 1.024 minutes. Scheduled Arrival Time was also significant (Estimate = -0.0009, SE = 0.00006, t = -16.43, p < .001), indicating that arrival delays decreased for flights scheduled to arrive later in the day. Both JFK (Estimate = -2.8, SE = 0.096, t = -29.48, p < .001) and LGA (Estimate = -1.46, SE = 0.085, t = -17.21, p < .001) has smaller arrival delays than EWR, by about 2 and 1 minutes respectively. Finally, air time was predictive of arrival delay (Estimate = 0.8, SE = 0.0022, t = 366.64, p < .001), indicating that for each additional minute in the air, arrival delays increased by 0.8 minutes.

When Should You Use Mixed Models?

Whenever you have nested data.

When Should You NOT use Mixed Models

When you dont have nested data. Fall back on regressions or ANOVAs is those situations.
